<doc id="20961" wikidata="Q205243" url="?curid=20961" title="Möbius function">
<text>The Möbius function formula_1 is a multiplicative function in number theory introduced by the German mathematician August Ferdinand Möbius (also transliterated &quot;Moebius&quot;) in 1832. It is ubiquitous in elementary and analytic number theory and most often appears as part of its namesake the Möbius inversion formula. Following work of Gian-Carlo Rota in the 1960s, generalizations of the Möbius function were introduced into combinatorics, and are similarly denoted formula_2.

==Definition==
The Möbius function is defined by

:formula_3

The Möbius function can alternatively be represented as

: formula_4

where formula_5 is the Kronecker delta, formula_6 is the Liouville function, 
formula_7 is the number of distinct prime divisors of formula_8, and formula_9 is the number of prime factors of formula_8, counted with multiplicity.

Another characterization by Gauss is the sum of all primitive roots.

==Values==
The values of formula_1 for the first 50 positive numbers are



The first 50 values of the function are plotted below:
Larger values can be checked in: 
* Wolframalpha
* the b-file of OEIS

== Applications ==
=== Mathematical series ===
The Dirichlet series that generates the Möbius function is the (multiplicative) inverse of the Riemann zeta function; if formula_12 is a complex number with real part larger than 1 we have

:formula_13

This may be seen from its Euler product

:formula_14

Also:

* formula_15
* formula_16
* formula_17
* formula_18 where formula_19 is Euler&#x27;s constant.

The Lambert series for the Möbius function is

:formula_20
which converges for formula_21. For prime formula_22, we also have

:formula_23

=== Algebraic number theory ===
Gauss proved that for a prime number formula_24 the sum of its primitive roots is congruent to formula_25.

If formula_26 denotes the finite field of order formula_27 (where formula_27 is necessarily a prime power), then the number formula_29 of monic irreducible polynomials of degree formula_8 over formula_26 is given by

:formula_32

The Möbius function is used in the Möbius inversion formula.

===Physics===
The Möbius function also arises in the primon gas or free Riemann gas model of supersymmetry. In this theory, the fundamental particles or &quot;primons&quot; have energies formula_33. Under second quantization, multiparticle excitations are considered; these are given by formula_34 for any natural number formula_8. This follows from the fact that the factorization of the natural numbers into primes is unique.

In the free Riemann gas, any natural number can occur, if the primons are taken as bosons. If they are taken as fermions, then the Pauli exclusion principle excludes squares. The operator 
formula_36 that distinguishes fermions and bosons is then none other than the Möbius function formula_1.

The free Riemann gas has a number of other interesting connections to number theory, including the fact that the partition function is the Riemann zeta function. This idea underlies Alain Connes&#x27;s attempted proof of the Riemann hypothesis.

== Properties ==
The Möbius function is multiplicative (i.e., 
formula_38 whenever formula_39 and formula_40 are coprime).
Proof: Given two coprime numbers formula_41, we induct on formula_42. If formula_43, then formula_44. Otherwise, formula_45, so

:formula_46
The sum of the Möbius function over all positive divisors of formula_8 (including formula_8 itself and 1) is zero except when formula_49:

:formula_50

The equality above leads to the important Möbius inversion formula and is the main reason why formula_51 is of relevance in the theory of multiplicative and arithmetic functions.

Other applications of formula_1 in combinatorics are connected with the use of the Pólya enumeration theorem in combinatorial groups and combinatorial enumerations.

There is a formula for calculating the Möbius function without directly knowing the factorization of its argument:

:formula_53

i.e. formula_1 is the sum of the primitive formula_8-th roots of unity. (However, the computational complexity of this definition is at least the same as that of the Euler product definition.)

Other identities satisfied by the Möbius function include

:formula_56

and

:formula_57.

The first of these is a classical result while the second was published in 2020. Similar identities hold for the Mertens function.

=== Proof of the formula for the sum of formula_51 over divisors ===
The formula

:formula_59

can be written using Dirichlet convolution as:
formula_60
where formula_61 is the identity under the convolution.

One way of proving this formula is by noting that the Dirichlet convolution of two multiplicative functions is again multiplicative. Thus it suffices to prove the formula for powers of primes. Indeed, for any prime 
formula_24 and for any formula_63
:formula_64,
while for formula_49
:formula_66.

====Other proofs====
Another way of proving this formula is by using the identity

:formula_67

The formula above is then a consequence of the fact that the formula_8th roots of unity sum to 0, since each formula_8th root of unity is a primitive formula_70th root of unity for exactly one divisor formula_70 of formula_8.

However it is also possible to prove this identity from first principles. First note that it is trivially true when formula_49. Suppose then that formula_74. Then there is a bijection between the factors formula_70 of formula_8 for which formula_77 and the subsets of the set of all prime factors of formula_8. The asserted result follows from the fact that every non-empty finite set has an equal number of odd- and even-cardinality subsets.

This last fact can be shown easily by induction on the cardinality formula_79 of a non-empty finite set formula_80. First, if formula_81, there is exactly one odd-cardinality subset of formula_80, namely formula_80 itself, and exactly one even-cardinality subset, namely formula_84. Next, if 
formula_85, then divide the subsets of formula_80 into two subclasses depending on whether they contain or not some fixed element formula_87 in formula_80. There is an obvious bijection between these two subclasses, pairing those subsets that have the same complement relative to the subset formula_89. Also, one of these two subclasses consists of all the subsets of the set formula_90, and therefore, by the induction hypothesis, has an equal number of odd- and even-cardinality subsets. These subsets in turn correspond bijectively to the even- and odd-cardinality formula_89-containing subsets of formula_80. The inductive step follows directly from these two bijections.

A related result is that the binomial coefficients exhibit alternating entries of odd and even power which sum symmetrically.

===Average order===
The mean value (in the sense of average orders) of the Möbius function is zero. This statement is, in fact, equivalent to the prime number theorem.

===formula_1 sections===
formula_94 if and only if formula_8 is divisible by the square of a prime. The first numbers with this property are

:4, 8, 9, 12, 16, 18, 20, 24, 25, 27, 28, 32, 36, 40, 44, 45, 48, 49, 50, 52, 54, 56, 60, 63, ... .

If formula_8 is prime, then formula_97, but the converse is not true. The first non prime formula_8 for which formula_97 is formula_100. The first such numbers with three distinct prime factors (sphenic numbers) are

:30, 42, 66, 70, 78, 102, 105, 110, 114, 130, 138, 154, 165, 170, 174, 182, 186, 190, 195, 222, ... .

and the first such numbers with 5 distinct prime factors are

:2310, 2730, 3570, 3990, 4290, 4830, 5610, 6006, 6090, 6270, 6510, 6630, 7410, 7590, 7770, 7854, 8610, 8778, 8970, 9030, 9282, 9570, 9690, ... .

== Mertens function ==
In number theory another arithmetic function closely related to the Möbius function is the Mertens function, defined by

:formula_101

for every natural number . This function is closely linked with the positions of zeroes of the Riemann zeta function. See the article on the Mertens conjecture for more information about the connection between formula_102 and the Riemann hypothesis.

From the formula

:formula_103

it follows that the Mertens function is given by

:formula_104

where formula_105 is the Farey sequence of order formula_8.

This formula is used in the proof of the Franel–Landau theorem.

==Generalizations==
===Incidence algebras===
In combinatorics, every locally finite partially ordered set (poset) is assigned an incidence algebra. One distinguished member of this algebra is that poset&#x27;s &quot;Möbius function&quot;. The classical Möbius function treated in this article is essentially equal to the Möbius function of the set of all positive integers partially ordered by divisibility. See the article on incidence algebras for the precise definition and several examples of these general Möbius functions.

===Popovici&#x27;s function===
Constantin Popovici defined a generalised Möbius function 
formula_107 to be the formula_108-fold Dirichlet convolution of the Möbius function with itself. It is thus again a multiplicative function with

:formula_109

where the binomial coefficient is taken to be zero if formula_110. The definition may be extended to complex formula_108 by reading the binomial as a polynomial in formula_108.

